{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493154","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493154"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:58:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:58:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1239"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1239","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1239"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.33,0.15,0.48,0.03,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1239"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104233"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1239","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1239"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1239"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86570"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"875"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7291"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7755"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8625"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37423"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104233","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104233"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 69-year-old man presents with a four-year history of difficulty in swallowing which has been getting steadily worse and it now takes him 20 minutes to eat a sandwich. During this time, he has lost about 5 kg in weight. He does not have any other health issues and does not use any medications.\u00a0The physical examination is unremarkable. A barium swallow is arranged (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Para-oesophageal hernia","Carcinoma of the oesophagus","Oesophageal diverticulum","Peptic oesophageal stricture","Diffuse oesophageal spasm"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe contrast study shows a large \u003Cstrong\u003Eoesophageal diverticulum\u003C/strong\u003E containing food residue at the lower end of the oesophagus.\u00a0Many of these diverticulae are asymptomatic and the patient tends to present with problems related to the underlying motility disorder - as in the present case. The underlying problem here is achalasia, the increased pressure and muscle contractions associated with achalasia can cause the oesophagus to weaken and stretch, leading to the formation of a pouch or sac called an oesophageal diverticulum. The diverticulum can fill with food, saliva, or other materials, causing further symptoms such as regurgitation, bad breath, and weight loss.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn a patient presenting with dysphagia and weight loss it is obviously important to rule out \u003Cstrong\u003Ecarcinoma of the oesophagus. \u003C/strong\u003EHowever, a four year history of dysphagia would make such a diagnosis rather unlikely. In addition, the contrast study would more characteristically show an irregular stricture with dilatation superior and \u0027hold up\u0027, rather than an out-pouching with food material.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Epeptic oesophageal stricture\u003C/strong\u003E would show a well-defined area of narrowing of the oesophagus, but any outpouching (diverticulum) would be unusual. These strictures are rare complications of gastro-oesophageal reflux disease - and this patient does not have any symptoms suggestive of such a problem.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ediffuse oesophageal spasm\u003C/strong\u003E will only show an abnormality on contrast study 60% of the time. It can otherwise show \u0027corkscrew oesophagus\u0027 or non-peristaltic contractions where the contrast is pushed in two different directions. Furthermore, the clinical presentation is likely to be more variable dysphagia and chest pain in both occurrence and severity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Epara-oesophageal hernia\u003C/strong\u003E would show coarse thick gastric folds in the pouch above the hiatus, potentially a tortuous oesophagus. Contrary to paraoesophageal hernia there is still oesophagus seen below the pouch, but these can easily be misread as paraoesophageal hernia by radiologists.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Barium swallow study can be a useful tool to differentiate causes of dysphagia, particularly long-standing symptoms, where a motility problem is suspected."],"references":["Niknejad M. Esophageal carcinoma: Radiology reference article [Internet]. Radiopaedia Blog RSS. Radiopaedia.org; 2022 [cited 2022Dec1]. Available from: https://radiopaedia.org/articles/oesophageal-carcinoma-1","Bell DJ. Diffuse esophageal spasm: Radiology reference article [Internet]. Radiopaedia Blog RSS. Radiopaedia.org; 2021 [cited 2022Dec1]. Available from: https://radiopaedia.org/articles/diffuse-oesophageal-spasm","Anan RA. Hiatus hernia: Radiology reference article [Internet]. Radiopaedia Blog RSS. Radiopaedia.org; 2022 [cited 2022Dec1]. Available from: https://radiopaedia.org/articles/hiatus-hernia"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86570"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1239"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19651"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19651","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19651"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/92107e6f-be2b-42e0-b2c0-17a10e325db5.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/92107e6f-be2b-42e0-b2c0-17a10e325db5.